hints_latex:
We have

\begin{align*}
f(x)^2=\frac{1}{x^{2p}}.
\end{align*}

Are there any values of \emph{p} that makes this integral special
compared to other values?

sols_latex:
For similar reasons to
{part
(a)} we will have two cases because we will have to worry about the
integral we are doing. There will be a unique situation if we are ever
integrating \emph{1/x} which occurs when \emph{p=1/2} because

\begin{align*}
V=\int_{1}^B\pi\left [ \frac{1}{x^p} \right ]^2 dx=\int_{1}^B\pi\frac{1}{x^{2p}} dx.
\end{align*}

If $p\neq{}1/2$ then when we rotate the function
$y = f(x) = \frac{1}{x^p}$ about the \emph{x}-axis over the interval
{[}1,\emph{B}{]}, the volume obtained is

\begin{align*}
V &= \int_{1}^{B} \pi \left [ \frac{1}{x^p} \right ]^2 dx = \pi \int_{1}^{B} \frac{1}{x^{2p}} dx = \pi \int_{1}^{B} x^{-2p} dx \\
&= \pi \left [ \frac{x^{-2p+1}}{-2p+1} \right ]_{1}^{B} = \frac{\pi}{1-2p} \left ( B^{1-2p} - 1 \right )
\end{align*}

If \emph{p=1/2} then

\begin{align*}
V&= \int_1^B\pi\left[\frac{1}{x^{1/2}}\right]^2dx=\pi\int_1^B\frac{1}{x}dx\\
&=\pi\left[\ln{x}\right]_{x=1}^{x=B}=\pi\ln{B}
\end{align*}

statement_latex:
Consider the curve given by

\begin{align*}
\displaystyle y = f(x) = \frac{1}{x^{p}}
\end{align*}

for $\displaystyle 1 \leq x \leq B$ where $\displaystyle p,B$ are
constants with $\displaystyle B > 1$ and $\displaystyle p > 0$.

(b) Compute the volume obtained by revolving the same region about the
\emph{x}-axis. (Later we will refer to this volume as V).
